<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Aurivillius" baseAuthorityYear="1892" class="Maxillopoda" family="Heteralepadidae" genus="Heteralepas" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heteralepas japonica" order="Pedunculata" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Heteralepas japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed in Indo-west Pacific: Indian Ocean; Australia; Singapore, Malacca Str., Indonesia; Malay Archipelago; Vietnam; Condor Island; S China Sea; E China Sea; Taiwan, Philippines; S Japan; NE New Zealand; fouling hard rock substrata, crabs, gorgonians, antipatharians, deep-sea cables; 48-500 m (
<bibRefCitation author="Jones, DS" journalOrPublisher="Raffles Bulletin of Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="241 - 311" refId="B36" refString="Jones, DS, Hosie, AM, 2016. A checklist of the barnacles (Cirripedia: Thoracica) of Singapore and neighbouring waters. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology 34: 241 - 311" title="A checklist of the barnacles (Cirripedia: Thoracica) of Singapore and neighbouring waters." volume="34" year="2016">Jones and Hosie 2016</bibRefCitation>
). In this study, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Aurivillius" baseAuthorityYear="1892" class="Maxillopoda" family="Heteralepadidae" genus="Heteralepas" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heteralepas japonica" order="Pedunculata" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Heteralepas japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was found attached to cable moorings in Lifamatola Sea and Halmahera Sea (a map with the occurrence of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Aurivillius" baseAuthorityYear="1892" class="Maxillopoda" family="Heteralepadidae" genus="Heteralepas" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heteralepas japonica" order="Pedunculata" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Heteralepas japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Moluccas is shown in Suppl. material 1: Fig. S1).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
The external appearance of this species is extremely variable (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1469-7998.1927.tb07432.x" author="Nilsson-Cantell, CA" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="743 - 790" refId="B47" refString="Nilsson-Cantell, CA, 1927. Some barnacles in the British Museum (Nat. Hist.). Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London 1927 (3): 743 - 790, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1469-7998.1927.tb07432.x" title="Some barnacles in the British Museum (Nat. Hist.)." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1469-7998.1927.tb07432.x" volume="1927" year="1927">Nilsson-Cantell 1927</bibRefCitation>
). After an extensive study of 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. japonica" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, Nilsson-Cantell could not distinguish 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. japonica" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. indica" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="species" species="indica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. indica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Gruvel, 1901) and placed the latter in synonymy with 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. japonica" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and later authors have followed this suggestion (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Broch, H" journalOrPublisher="Videnskabelige Meddelelser fra dansk naturhistorisk Forening i Kjobenhaven," pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="1 - 146" refId="B5" refString="Broch, H, 1931. Papers from Dr Th. Mortensen's Pacific Expedition 1914-1916. LVI. Indomalayan Cirripedia. Videnskabelige Meddelelser fra dansk naturhistorisk Forening i Kjobenhaven, 91: 1 - 146" title="Papers from Dr Th. Mortensen's Pacific Expedition 1914 - 1916. LVI. Indomalayan Cirripedia." volume="91" year="1931">Broch 1931</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5134/174591" author="Utinomi, H" journalOrPublisher="Molecular phylogenetics and evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B76" refString="Utinomi, H, 1958. Studies on the Cirripedian Fauna of Japan. VII. Cirripeds from Sagami Bay. Publications of the Seto Marine Biological Laboratory, 6(3): 281-311. Figs 1-10. https://doi.org/10.5134/174591" title="Studies on the Cirripedian Fauna of Japan. VII. Cirripeds from Sagami Bay. Publications of the Seto Marine Biological Laboratory, 6 (3): 281 - 311. Figs 1 - 10." url="https://doi.org/10.5134/174591" year="1958">Utinomi 1958</bibRefCitation>
). At the same time, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1469-7998.1927.tb07432.x" author="Nilsson-Cantell, CA" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="743 - 790" refId="B47" refString="Nilsson-Cantell, CA, 1927. Some barnacles in the British Museum (Nat. Hist.). Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London 1927 (3): 743 - 790, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1469-7998.1927.tb07432.x" title="Some barnacles in the British Museum (Nat. Hist.)." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1469-7998.1927.tb07432.x" volume="1927" year="1927">Nilsson-Cantell (1927)</bibRefCitation>
